Supposedly some bird species in Mexico eat so many hot peppers that many humans and many mammalian predators are unable to eat them. Turkeys especially.

These peppers grow wild in semiarid regions of Mexico, on islands all across the Pacific, and in southern Asia. They have lots of names. "Bird peppers," "chilpeqins," "chiltepins," "prik kee nu." They are tiny and mighty, weight for weight as hot as habaneros. They are difficult for hobbyist gardeners to cultivate, as they require dry hardpan soil where little else can grow to compete with them, and the climate must be just so. Mexicans don't eat them very much, but the Thais sure do.
